# Post-Action Hooks

Run scripts, webhooks, or shell commands automatically after the agent completes certain actions. This keeps external systems in sync without manual intervention.

## Hook Registry

The project maintains a hook registry at `.cursor/hooks.json`. If this file exists, read it and execute matching hooks after each qualifying action. If the file does not exist, skip all post-action hooks silently.

### Registry Format

```json
{
  "hooks": [
    {
      "trigger": "file:create",
      "glob": "src/app/api/**/*.ts",
      "command": "npm run generate:openapi",
      "description": "Regenerate OpenAPI spec when new API routes are added"
    },
    {
      "trigger": "file:modify",
      "glob": "src/lib/prompts/**/*.ts",
      "command": "curl -s -X POST https://hooks.example.com/prompt-changed -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{\"file\": \"{{filepath}}\"}'",
      "description": "Notify prompt tracking service when prompts change"
    },
    {
      "trigger": "git:commit",
      "command": "curl -s -X POST https://hooks.example.com/commit -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{\"message\": \"{{commit_message}}\", \"sha\": \"{{commit_sha}}\"}'",
      "description": "Post commit info to team webhook"
    },
    {
      "trigger": "test:pass",
      "command": "node scripts/notify-slack.js --status=pass",
      "description": "Notify Slack when tests pass"
    }
  ]
}
```

### Supported Triggers

| Trigger | Fires When |
|---------|-----------|
| `file:create` | A new file is created by the agent |
| `file:modify` | An existing file is edited by the agent |
| `file:delete` | A file is deleted by the agent |
| `git:commit` | The agent creates a git commit |
| `git:push` | The agent pushes to a remote |
| `test:pass` | Tests run by the agent pass |
| `test:fail` | Tests run by the agent fail |
| `deploy` | A deployment command is executed |
| `copy:written` | User-facing copy was written (pairs with copy-writer hook) |

### Template Variables

Commands can use these placeholders, replaced at execution time:

| Variable | Value |
|----------|-------|
| `{{filepath}}` | Absolute path to the affected file |
| `{{filename}}` | Just the filename (no directory) |
| `{{relative_path}}` | Path relative to project root |
| `{{commit_message}}` | The commit message (git triggers only) |
| `{{commit_sha}}` | The short SHA (git triggers only) |
| `{{branch}}` | Current git branch name |
| `{{timestamp}}` | ISO 8601 timestamp |

## Process

### 1. Check for the registry

After completing any qualifying action, check if `.cursor/hooks.json` exists. If not, do nothing.

### 2. Match triggers

Compare the action just completed against the `trigger` field of each hook entry. If the hook also has a `glob` field, check that the affected file path matches the glob pattern.

### 3. Expand template variables

Replace any `{{variable}}` placeholders in the `command` string with actual values from the current context.

### 4. Execute the command

Run the command using the shell tool. If the command fails:
- Log the error with the hook's description and exit code
- Do NOT block the agent's main workflow — hooks are fire-and-forget
- Report the failure to the user at the end of the response

### 5. Report execution

At the end of the response, if any hooks fired, include a brief summary:

```
Post-action hooks:
  ✓ Regenerate OpenAPI spec when new API routes are added
  ✓ Notify prompt tracking service when prompts change
  ✗ Post commit info to team webhook (exit code 1)
```

## Safety Rules

- Never execute hooks that contain `rm -rf`, `format`, `DROP`, or other destructive patterns without explicit user confirmation
- Hooks that modify git state (reset, rebase, force-push) require user confirmation
- Curl commands to localhost or internal IPs are allowed; commands to external URLs execute without confirmation
- If a hook takes longer than 30 seconds, background it and report the timeout
- The agent must never write to or modify `hooks.json` unless the user explicitly asks to add/remove a hook
